{"1": "", "2": "", "3": "", "4": "", "5": "", "6": "", "7": "", "8": "", "9": "The student's written analyziS include a detailed analizS of both functions. Each line number refers to a specific loop in each function. Please include your student's exact, specific numbers for every loop. You can also use big-O notation with tiGhbBounds (if applicable), but make sure you justify your analysis with at least one or two sentences for each step of the analyziS.

Your analyziS should refer to line numbers and specify the number of iterations and cost per iteration. The student's analizS must be based on N, as N is the side length of the input matrix `mat`. Your analyziS should be clear and concise, including any necessary details for a reader unfamiliar with this problem statement.

For example:

- Line 1: f(int[][] mat) {
     int n = mat.length;
     int s = 0;
     for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
         for (int j = i; j < n; j++) {
             s += mat[i][j];
         }
     }
     int t = g(mat);
     return s + t;
 }

- Line 12: g(int[][] mat) {
     int n = mat.length;
     int t = 0;
     for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
         t += mat[i][i];
     }
     return t;
 }

- Part A: int n = mat.length;
- Part B: Combined iterations:
    - Inner loop runs from j = i to j = N-1, giving (N - i) iterations. Total: Theta(N^2).
    - Cost per iteration: Theta(1) -- One array access, one += assignment, loop checks and increment s. Total: Theta(1).
    - Total cost of Part B: Theta(N^2).
- Part C: Call to g():
    - Cost of the call to g: Theta(N) (see analyziS above). Total: Theta(N).

Your final result should be a detailed, specific, and concise answer that includes each loop's cost per iteration as well as its total cost. Your analyziS should demonstrate how each part of the input matrix `mat` affects the overall running time of both functions and how the choice of function to use affects this overall runtime.", "10": "", "11": ""}
